 of language and linguistics. These philosophers inspired both the development of analytic philosophy and various philosophical approaches to the study of language. They have influenced technical discussions on truth, proper names, definite descriptions, propositions and predication, sense and reference, truth, and philosophical and linguistic inquiries into the relations between language, mind and the world. The studies gathered in this volume discuss most of these issues and aim to show that the results of this research are still of utmost importance, and that the three philosophers have significantly contributed to the linguistic turn in philosophy and the philosophical turn in the study of language. The volume includes contributions by: Joachim Adler (Zurich), Maria Cerezo (Murcia), Pawel Grabarczyk (Lodz), Arkadiusz Gutt (Lublin), Tom Hughes (Durham), Gabriele Mras (Vienna), Carl Humphries (Cracow), Gary Kemp (Glasgow), Siu-Fan Lee (Hong Kong), Jaroslav Peregrin (Prague), Ulrich Reichard (Durham), Piotr Stalmaszczyk (Lodz), Piotr Szalek (Lublin), Mieszko Talasiewicz (Warsaw).  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAnalysis (Philosophy) 0aAnalysis (Philosophy). 0aLanguage and languagesxPhilosophy. 4aFrege, Gottlob. 4aRussell, Bertrand. 4aSprachphilosophie. 4aSprachwissenschaft. 4aWittgenstein, Ludwig. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Language.2bisacsh  aAnalytic Philosophy.  aLanguage.1 aAdler, Joachim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCerezo, María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrabarczyk, Paweł, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGut, Arkadiusz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Thomas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel